Date: Wed 7 Dec 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AP via The Moscow Times, Issue 3311, Page 5, 7 Dec 2005 [edited]
<http://www.themoscowtimes.com/stories/2005/12/07/043.html>

Ukraine Backs State of Emergency to Fight Bird Flu
-----------------------------------------------
Ukraine's parliament on Tuesday [6 Dec 2005] endorsed President Viktor
Yushchenko's decision to declare a state of emergency to combat a bird flu
outbreak, despite some lawmakers' claims that the move was excessive.
Yushchenko put 3 regions in the Crimean peninsula under an indefinite state
of emergency on Saturday [3 Dec 2005], after the country recorded its 1st
case of type H5 bird flu.
The parliament supported the measure following a raucous session, but urged
the president to specify the order by saying how long the state of
emergency would last and what extra powers it gave local officials.
"Today it is better to do much more than necessary than tomorrow to have
this problem throughout the whole of Ukrainian territory," Emergency
Situations Minister Viktor Baloga said during an emergency parliamentary
session. Under Ukraine's Constitution, parliament must meet within 2 days
of the president's order to confirm the state of emergency, which can be
declared when there is a "threat to the population's life and health."
It was the 1st time since the 1991 Soviet collapse that a state of
emergency was enacted in Ukraine, Baloga said.
Baloga defended the government's response as "justified," even as lawmakers
grumbled that when bird flu appeared in neighboring Russia, a state of
emergency was not declared. They also complained that Yushchenko did not
specify when the emergency state would end. On Monday [5 Dec 2005],
Yushchenko suggested it would last 2 weeks. Mykhailo Pozhivanov, a lawmaker
in Yushchenko's party, warned the measure could hurt Ukraine's image and
scare away tourists from the Black Sea resort area.
Veterinary authorities have detected new bird flu cases in a southern
Russian region, but it is yet to be determined whether it is the deadly
Asian strain, Interfax reported Tuesday [6 Dec 2005], citing a regional
veterinary official. [Information on this report -- referring to southern
Russia -- is requested. - Mod.AS]
--
